<HEADLINE>
MIXED RACIAL PRIMARY, JUNIOR HIGH STUDENTS EXCEED 80,000: DGBAS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March  4 (CNA) 03/04/07  20:25:21 (By Y.L.Kao)
</P>
<P>
The number of local junior high and elementary school students
with a foreign- born parent has broken the 80,000 mark, the
Directorate-General of Budget, Accounting and Statistics (DGBAS)
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, the number of elementary schoolchildren and junior
high school students born to couples consisting of a Taiwan
national and a foreigner totaled 80,166 in the 2006 academic
year, marking a sharp increase from 60,258 registered in the
previous school year, DGBAS officials said.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 70,797 were elementary schoolchildren, accounting for
3.9 percent of the country's total and increasing 1 percent from
the previous academic year.
</P>
<P>
The  number  of  junior  high  school  students  born  to mixed-
nationality families inched up 0.3 percent to reach 9,369,
accounting for 1percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
According to the DGBAS tallies,  the offshore counties of
Lienchiang, Kinmen and Penghu registered the three highest ratios
of the schoolchildren born to foreign mothers or foreign fathers.
</P>
<P>
Lienhciang County, which refers to the outlying island of Matsu,
topped the list, with one out of every six elelmntary
schoolchildren born to mixed- nationality families, or 16.6
percent of the county's total, followed by Kinmen County's 6.5
percent and Penghu County's 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The DGBAS tallies also showed that northern Taiwan had 35,057
mixed racial junior high students and elementary schoolchildren;
southern Taiwan had 21,749; and central Taiwan had 21,250.
</P>
<P>
Broken down by the nationality of their parents, 35.9 percent
have a parent from China, Hong Kong or Macau; 22.6 percent from
Indonesia and 20.7 percent from Vietnam; the number from Vietnam
marked an increase of 2.6 percent over the previous academic
year.
</P>
